# pqcbom self-scan policy for THIS repository (the scanner's own source).
#
# WHY THIS FILE EXISTS — read before crying foul:
# A crypto SCANNER's source necessarily NAMES every algorithm it detects: its rule tables, its
# adversarial test corpus, and its accuracy benchmarks are full of "MD5"/"RC4"/"RSA" strings by
# design. That is detection LOGIC and test DATA, not cryptographic USE. Without this policy a
# self-scan grades the scanner F for containing its own rules — a feedback loop, not a finding.
# Everything excluded below is one of: (a) rule/policy tables, (b) deliberately-vulnerable test
# fixtures, (c) test/benchmark harnesses asserting on vulnerable strings. The REAL crypto this
# package USES (ML-DSA-87, SLH-DSA, ML-KEM, Falcon verification, SHA-384/512) is NOT excluded.
# Delete this file and re-run for the raw, unfiltered lexical view — nothing is hidden, and the
# scan output states how many paths this policy excluded.

# (a) scanner rule tables + vendored copies (every rule names the algorithm it detects)
path:pqcbom.mjs
pqcbom-action/
path:pqcbom-plan.mjs
path:pqcbom-server.mjs
path:pqcbom-report.mjs
path:pqposture.mjs
path:pqshield.mjs
path:pqcompliance.mjs

# (b) deliberately-vulnerable test fixtures, demo target + generated sample packs
test-fixtures/
examples/
path:gen-sample-pack.mjs

# (c) test + benchmark harnesses (assert on vulnerable strings by design)
path:test*.mjs
path:test.js
path:accuracy-benchmark.mjs
path:structural-corpus.mjs
path:tamper-binding.mjs
path:assurance-properties.mjs
path:fuzz-*.mjs
deploy/
